          "title": "The half-baked cake — syncretism's self-defeating incompetence (7:8-10)",
          "body": "The chapter's second dominant metaphor arrives with equal force. 'Ephraim mixes himself with the nations; Ephraim has become a cake not turned.' The image is of flatbread cooked on a griddle — if not flipped at the right moment, it burns on the bottom while remaining raw on top. The result is inedible: destroyed on one side, unfinished on the other, useful for nothing. This is what cultural and religious syncretism has produced in Ephraim. By mixing covenant faith with Baalism, by adopting the religious and political habits of surrounding nations, Israel has become neither genuinely Yahwistic nor genuinely Canaanite — it is competent at nothing and formed in nothing. The pastoral irony is verse 9: 'Strangers devour his strength, yet he does not know it.' The very nations Israel mingles with are eating his resources, his military capacity, his economic reserves — and Israel cannot perceive it. The gray hairs are already appearing; the nation is aging toward death; and Ephraim looks in the mirror and sees vigor. This spiritual obliviousness is itself a judgment: God has not yet given Israel up, but He has withdrawn the capacity for self-knowledge. Verse 10 applies the indictment canonically: 'the pride of Israel testifies against him' — the same phrase used in 5:5 — yet they have not returned to the LORD. The evidence has been mounting for years. The diagnosis is undeniable. The response is silence and more of the same."
